SIMPLE: err
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Err
<hw>Err</hw> <pr>(⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Erred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Erring</conjf> <pr>(?; 277, 85)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>errer</ets>, L. <ets>errare</ets>; akin to G. <ets>irren</ets>,
OHG. <ets>irran</ets>, v. t., <ets>irr⟦omac⟧n</ets>, v. i., OS.
<ets>irrien</ets>, Sw. <ets>irra</ets>, Dan. <ets>irre</ets>, Goth,
<ets>a⟦iacute⟧rzjan</ets> to lead astray, <ets>airzise</ets>
astray.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To wander; to roam; to stray.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Why wilt thou <xex>err</xex> from
me?⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Keble.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What seemeth to you, if there were to a man an hundred sheep and
one of them hath <qex>erred</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Wyclif (Matt. xviii.
12).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To deviate from the true course; to miss the thing
aimed at.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧My jealous aim might <xex>err</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To miss intellectual truth; to fall into error; to
mistake in judgment or opinion; to be mistaken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The man may <qex>err</qex> in his judgment of circumstances.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To deviate morally from the right way; to go astray,
in a figurative sense; to do wrong; to sin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do they not <qex>err</qex> that devise evil?</q> <rj><qau>Prov.
xiv. 22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To offend, as by erring.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Errable</ent>⟦br⟧
